As a beekeeper, nothing beats sharing your passion with others🐝 

We decided to offer hive tours this season, not knowing what to expect or who’d even be(e) interested in such an experience! We’re happy to report that it’s been nothing short of PERFECT, and it’s incredibly exciting to add a few more beekeepers to our growing community.

If you’d like to join us for this Airbnb experience, follow the link in our bio 🐝

Who splits beehives during a hive tour? WE DO 🔥 

For our Airbnb experience today, we inspected 3 hives after a honey tasting. One of those hives had recently swarmed, and we felt like another (cast swarm) was on the way 😱 

So, we made two splits from this monster hive! And I think we made two new beekeepers as well 👍

A “swarm” is a beehive’s method of reproduction. Basically, the hive divides into two distinct hives, one of which is the swarm led by the original queen! The queen travels with the swarm to a new location, to start a new colony. 

Only about 1/3 swarms survive in the wild, so we try to catch as many as possible! #swarm #savethebees #beekeeping
#swarm #bees #Spring #beekeeping

If you’re new to beekeeping, we’re harvesting queen bees! Some beekeepers focus on honey or pollination, but we’re all about making more bees. These queens will hatch in about a week, and then we’ll give them a hive to rule 👸

People often ask “how can you tell who’s the queen?” and this picture is the perfect example of the worker/queen size difference.

Queens aren’t much wider than a worker bee; it mostly has to do with abdomen length…aka the bee butt. 

Some people get the impression that queens are a different color, but that’s not true! They just have a big booty so they can reach the base of honeycomb and lay an egg. 

As a new beekeeper, it can be difficult to find the queen. But don’t get discouraged! Just look for the long abdomen, and typically there’s a circle of bees surrounding her.

In North Carolina, our flowers barely bloom from June to August. So, WE FEED! But because nothing is blooming, the bees rob each other.

It’s a delicate balance, but every drop of spilt sugar water will attract neighboring hives. So don’t spill it!
